[[File:Marsh-Custom-House-Murals.jpg|thumb|[[Reginald Marsh (artist)|Reginald Marsh]] and his assistants completed 2,300 square feet of murals in fresco for the rotunda of the [[Alexander Hamilton U.S. Custom House]] (1937), the Treasury Relief Art Project's most extensive and successful project in New York.]]
The '''Treasury Relief Art Project''' was a [[New Deal]] arts program that commissioned visual artists to provide artistic decoration for existing Federal buildings during the [[Great Depression in the United States]]. A project of the [[United States Department of the Treasury]], TRAP was administered by the [[Section of Painting and Sculpture]] and funded by the [[Works Progress Administration]], which provided assistants employed through the [[Federal Art Project]]. The Treasury Relief Art Project also created murals and sculpture for [[Public Works Administration]] housing projects. TRAP was established July 21, 1935, and continued through June 30, 1938.

==Program==
[[File:Marsh-Hudson-Ambrose-Block-Custom-House.jpg|left|thumb|Murals in fresco by Reginald Marsh for the rotunda of the Alexander Hamilton U.S. Custom House (1937)]]
The Treasury Relief Art Project was created July 21, 1935,<ref name="NARA TRAP">{{cite web |url=https://research.archives.gov/id/532328 |title=Treasury Relief Art Project, 1935–1939 |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher=National Archives Catalog |access-date=2016-04-20}}</ref> with an allocation of $530,784 from the Works Progress Administration. The project was conceived and overseen by Treasury Department arts administrator [[Edward Bruce (New Deal)|Edward Bruce]]. Artist [[Olin Dows]] was chief of the Treasury Relief Art Project;<ref name="Kalfatovic">{{cite book |last=Kalfatovic |first=Martin R. |date=1994 |title=The New Deal Fine Arts Projects: A Bibliography, 1933–1992 |url=https://archive.org/stream/newdealfineartsp00kalf#page/n4/mode/1up |location=Metuchen, New Jersey |publisher=The Scarecrow Press |isbn=0-8108-2749-2}}</ref>{{Rp|xxiv–xxx}} Cecil H. Jones, who later succeeded Dows, was assistant chief. Forbes Watson was director.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/treasury-relief-art-project-selected-administrative-and-business-records-9773 |title=Treasury Relief Art Project selected administrative and business records, 1935–1939|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=Archives of American Art |publisher=Smithsonian Institution |access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref> Unlike the concurrent Treasury [[Section of Painting and Sculpture]], TRAP was a work-relief program, subject to the income and employment standards of the WPA.<ref name="Kalfatovic"/>{{Rp|xxix}} The September 1935 announcement of the program estimated that it would employ 400 to 500 artists.<ref name="Kalfatovic"/>{{Rp|38}} 

The principal mission of the Treasury Relief Art Project was to provide artistic decoration for existing Federal buildings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gsa.gov/portal/content/101384 |title=New Deal Artwork: GSA's Inventory Project |website= |publisher=[[General Services Administration]] |access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref> These projects could not be performed by the Section of Painting and Sculpture,<ref name="O'Connor"/>{{Rp|62}} which commissioned art for new construction using a percentage of the budget overseen by the Treasury Department's procurement division.<ref name="Kalfatovic"/>{{Rp|xxvi–xxvii}} The Treasury Relief Art Project was funded by the WPA. The Section supervised the creative output of TRAP, and selected a master artist for each project. Assistants were then chosen by the artist from the rolls of the WPA [[Federal Art Project]].<ref name="O'Connor">{{cite journal |last=O'Connor |first=Francis V. |date=Autumn 1969 |title=The New Deal Art Projects in New York  |journal=The American Art Journal |publisher=Kennedy Galleries, Inc. |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=58–79 |jstor=1593876 }}</ref>{{Rp|62–63}}

As chief of the Treasury Relief Art Project, Dows was responsible for maintaining financial records for relief and non-relief personnel. A fixed proportion of all workers was to be taken from the relief rolls—initially 90 percent,<ref name="Kalfatovic"/>{{Rp|xxxii}} but revised to 75 percent in December 1935.<ref name="Kalfatovic"/>{{Rp|47}}

Although it was regarded as a success, the Treasury Relief Art Project was ended June 30, 1938.<ref name="Kalfatovic"/>{{Rp|xxx}}

