At a total cost of $833,784,<ref name="O'Connor"/>{{Rp|63}} 89 mural projects and 65 sculpture projects were completed under the Treasury Relief Art Project, as well as 10,000 easel paintings that were distributed to Federal offices.<ref name="NARA TRAP"/>

[[Reginald Marsh (artist)|Reginald Marsh]] was the master artist commissioned in 1937 to create a cycle of murals in [[fresco]] for the rotunda of the [[Alexander Hamilton U.S. Custom House]]. Marsh's team of assistants included Oliver M. Baker, [[Xavier J. Barile]], Charles Bateman, [[Mary Fife Laning|Mary Fife]], [[Lloyd Lozes Goff]], [[Ludwig Mactarian]], John Poehler, Erica Volsung<ref name="O'Connor"/>{{Rp|72–73}} and J. Walkley, students he knew from his teaching at the [[Art Students League of New York|Art Students League]].<ref name="NYC Landmarks Custom House">{{cite web |url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1022.pdf |title=United States Custom House Interior |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=January 9, 1979 |website= |publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] |access-date=2016-04-26}}</ref>{{Rp|6}} It was TRAP's most extensive and successful project in New York,<ref name="O'Connor"/>{{Rp|72}} encompassing 2,300 square feet.<ref name="NYC Landmarks Custom House"/>{{Rp|6}}

