{{div col end}}

In addition to producing artwork for Federal buildings, the Treasury Relief Art Project created murals and sculpture for [[Public Works Administration]] housing projects in Boston, Camden, Chicago, Cleveland, New York, Washington, D.C.<ref name="Kalfatovic"/>{{Rp|xxx}} and Stamford.<ref name="Fairfield Court"/>

==Artists==
To maintain its high artistic standards, the Treasury Relief Art Project commissioned only a small number of artists—356 workers at its peak<ref name="Kalfatovic"/>{{Rp|xxiv}} in 1936. [[Richmond Barthé]], Ahron Ben-Shmuel, [[Paul Cadmus]], [[Marion Greenwood]], [[William Gropper]], [[Reginald Marsh (artist)|Reginald Marsh]] and [[Heinz Warneke]] were among the master artists who led projects.<ref name="NARA TRAP"/> A complete list of projects and artists employed by TRAP is included in the final report held by the Smithsonian's [[Archives of American Art]].<ref name="Kalfatovic"/>{{Rp|185}}

